      {
        "id": 4509084,
        "name": "Steve Costigan",
        "username": "Steve_Costigan",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/steve_costigan/{size}/273510_2.png",
        "created_at": "2024-11-18T06:19:00.924Z",
        "cooked": "<p>I have several bottles of the 2011 and somehow haven\u2019t gotten around to trying one until this weekend. Only my second or third vintage from this producer. Very dark in color a deep brambly fruit with blackberry, dark cherry and also framboise notes hovering above everything and plenty of tannic structure. Only somewhat moderately complex in the nose with herbal notes. It seems quite young but tannins are settling in. Everything is in balance and although the extraction and depth of this wine are large scale I got no sense of over ripeness. Huge but nonetheless I would have guessed St. Emilion if served blind but I have to admit once or twice it made me think of Saxum.</p>\n<p>I get that full throttle right bank wines of this aren\u2019t well liked by many here. I swing both ways and appreciate this style as I do far more elegant wines.  They just have to be well made, balanced and without any hint of over ripe fruit character.</p>\n<p>I was taken aback to be confronted by a wine of this concentration given the problems of this cold/wet vintage. I heard that there was no way to get the alcohol levels reported in some 2011s without chaptalization but chaptalization doesn\u2019t explain the concentration and depth of this wine. Parker wrote something that this estate makes wines for 19th century tastes but never understood exactly what that means (or how he would know). But I can see that this might mean wines of great depth and extraction and plenty of backbone without too much ripeness, which is what this was.</p>\n<p>I liked it and look forward to my remaining bottles, more very good rather than excellent 4- out of 5.</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 5,
        "updated_at": "2024-11-18T06:21:03.609Z",
